`Exchange.getIn()` will contain the initial message for the route (eg the message created by a `Consumer`) whereas `Exchange.getMessage()` will change over time as the message is transformed.

`Exchange.getOut()`, `Exchange.setOut(...)` and `Exchange.hasOut()` have been deprecated. Before they were deprecated we needed to write code such as

```java
Message message = exchange.hasOut() ? exchange.getOut() : exchange.getIn();
doStuff(message)
```

The &quot;out&quot; concept has been deprecated in favour of get/set &quot;message&quot; so we can now write code like
```java
Message message = exchange.getMessage();
doStuff(message)
```

If you look at [AbstractExchange.java](https://github.com/apache/camel/blob/007c4b6f7c054a01cf1426ea4ed32c7c0339ba71/core/camel-support/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/support/AbstractExchange.java#L560-L563) you can see `getMessage()` is calling the old deprecated methods
```java
class AbstractExchange implements ExtendedExchange {
    ...
    @Override
    public Message getMessage() {
        return hasOut() ? getOut() : getIn();
    }
    ...
}
```

